# Saved Shipping Addresses вҖ” Plan & Evaluation

## The Problem
Users must re-type their full shipping address every time they purchase. This is friction that reduces conversion rates.

## The 4 Industry Approaches

| # | Approach | Who Uses It | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| A | **Embed on User document** | Shopify, small-mid stores | Simple, fast reads, no joins, MongoDB best practice for 1:few | Max ~5 addresses per user (fine for e-commerce) |
| B | **Separate `Address` collection** | Amazon (millions of addresses) | Unlimited addresses, independent queries | Extra collection, needs `$lookup` joins, over-engineered for < 5 addresses |
| C | **LocalStorage only** | Budget MVPs | Zero server work | Lost on new device, no cross-device sync, not production-grade |
| D | **Stripe Customer address** | Stripe-native apps | Stripe handles storage | Vendor lock-in, can't display addresses without Stripe API calls, limited fields |

## My Recommendation: **Approach A вҖ” Embed on User Document**

> [!TIP]
> MongoDB's official guidance: "If a document has a 1:few relationship (like a user with 2-5 addresses), embed the related data as a subdocument array."

This is the best fit because:
- Users rarely have more than 3-5 shipping addresses
- Zero new collections (clean architecture)
- Single query to fetch user + addresses (no joins)
- Matches your existing `User` model pattern
- Used by Shopify, Etsy, and most mid-tier e-commerce platforms

---

## Implementation Plan

### Phase 1: Schema Update

**File:** `lib/models/User.ts`

```diff
 export interface IUser extends Document {
   firebaseUid: string;
   email: string;
   name?: string;
   role: "customer" | "admin";
+  shippingAddresses: IShippingAddress[];
 }

+interface IShippingAddress {
+  _id: Types.ObjectId;        // Auto-generated, used as address ID
+  label: string;              // "Home", "Office", "Mom's House"
+  fullName: string;
+  address: string;
+  city: string;
+  state: string;
+  zipCode: string;
+  country: string;
+  phone: string;
+  isDefault: boolean;         // One address marked as default
+}
```

- Cap at **5 addresses max** per user (server-side enforced)
- `isDefault` ensures only one address is primary
- `label` gives users a quick way to identify addresses

### Phase 2: Server Actions

**File:** `app/actions/address.ts` (new)

| Action | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `getSavedAddresses(userId)` | Fetch user's address array |
| `saveAddress(userId, address, label)` | Push new address (max 5 cap) |
| `deleteAddress(userId, addressId)` | Pull address from array |
| `setDefaultAddress(userId, addressId)` | Toggle `isDefault` flag |

All actions reuse the existing `TShippingForm` type from `lib/validations/checkout.ts` вҖ” no new validation schema needed (DRY).

### Phase 3: UI вҖ” Address Picker

**File:** `components/checkout/AddressPicker.tsx` (new)

Appears **above** the ShippingForm in Step 1:
- Shows saved addresses as selectable cards
- Clicking a card auto-fills the ShippingForm
- "Use a new address" button clears the form
- Checkbox: "Save this address for next time" with a label input

